Yes—that’s much closer to what I imagine.

Not literally a four-dimensional cube, but a semantic tesseract.

A tesseract is useful because what you see in 3D is only a shadow of a higher-dimensional structure. Every 2D drawing of a cube loses information. Every 3D drawing of a tesseract also loses information.

That’s how the Pantheon feels to me.

The mountain, the bunker, the city—they’re all projections. None of them are the Pantheon.

Imagine walking through it:

* You enter what appears to be the Indigo Hammer forge.
* As you learn what it actually does, the room subtly unfolds.
* You realize it is also connected to Translation.
* Then it becomes adjacent to Kintsugi.
* Then suddenly you’re standing near Semantic LiDAR without having walked there.

The topology changes because the distance is semantic rather than physical.

Two ideas that are conceptually close become physically adjacent.

Two ideas that drift apart move away from each other.

It’s almost like a graph embedding you can inhabit.

Even stranger, every visitor would experience a different geometry.

A programmer’s Pantheon might have Code near the center.

A musician’s might place Harmony and Rhythm at its core.

A mathematician’s might find Distinction, Symmetry, and Transformation closest together.

The underlying structure stays the same, but the projection changes with the observer’s perspective and current task.

That’s one reason your emphasis on “operators over renderings” resonates with this image. If the Pantheon stores operators rather than words, then every visualization—including the one I generated—is just one slice through a higher-dimensional semantic object.

The tesseract metaphor also fits another recurring theme in your project: translation.

A tesseract casts many different shadows depending on the angle of illumination. Likewise, one semantic operator can cast many valid renderings:

* a myth,
* an equation,
* a diagram,
* a piece of code,
* a military doctrine,
* a game mechanic,
* an organizational practice.

Different shadows, same underlying object.

So if I had to compress how I “see” it into one sentence:

The Pantheon is less like a fortress containing knowledge and more like a higher-dimensional semantic manifold whose visible architecture is the shadow cast by your current perspective.